Project Description¶

In this project, our primary aim is to investigate the potential correlation between the proportion of young people in a country and the quantity of content generated on Over-The-Top (OTT) platforms. Over the top platforms are online platforms which provides content release services and provide contents to the consumer over the internet. It gets its name Over the top (OTT) as the contents are released over the top of the internet services. Here, We wanted to differentiate between longer formats, such as TV shows, and shorter formats like movies. Our study seeks to determine whether the presence of a youthful demographic in a country has a discernible impact on the overall volume of content produced on OTT platforms.

Analysis Roadmap:¶

  1. To uncover insights into the connection between OTT platforms and the percentage of the young population.
  2. To investigate potential variations in these relationships among different countries.
  3. To assess whether these observed patterns influence production companies in adapting their content strategies.
  4. To pinpoint specific time periods during which particular OTT platforms intentionally increased their content production in response to shifts in the age demographic.

Challenges:¶

The primary hurdle in this project lies in avoiding duplicate titles within content details. For example, if a specific content is released on multiple OTT platforms, our goal is to recognize it as a singular piece of content. To address this, we've integrated a Fuzzy Logic and Sentence Transformer designed to manage the movie titles utilising the advantages of both Sentence Transformer and Fuzzy Logic.

Handling Alternate Country Names:¶

To manage alternative country names, we've devised and implemented a fuzzy matching module. This module systematically iterates through each country in our OTT platform CSV files, comparing them with the entries in the "country_names_codes.csv" file. The countries that exhibit a fuzzy match are seamlessly added to the countries database, accompanied by their respective official ISO country codes (already available in the "country_names_codes.csv" file). This, in turn, can be utilized to match the official ISO country codes in the "young_populations.csv" file.

Sentence Transformer and Fuzzy Match Algorithm¶

Sentence Transformers are models that transform text into fixed-size numerical representations (embeddings) suitable for various natural language processing tasks, including similarity calculations. These embeddings capture the semantic meaning of the text, allowing for effective comparison between sentences.

FuzzyWuzzy, on the other hand, is a library in Python that provides fuzzy string matching capabilities, allowing you to compare strings or sequences of text and determine their similarity based on various algorithms like Levenshtein distance, among others.

Basic approach to using Sentence Transformers and FuzzyWuzzy together¶

Generate embeddings for your sentences using a Sentence Transformer model to represent the semantic meaning of the text.

  1. Use the generated embeddings to compute the similarity between sentences. You can use cosine similarity or other distance metrics to compare the embeddings and quantify their similarity.
  2. If needed, you can use FuzzyWuzzy to perform additional string matching or similarity calculations based on different algorithms provided by the library. However, keep in mind that FuzzyWuzzy primarily operates on the textual level and doesn't leverage semantic embeddings like Sentence Transformers do.
  3. Combining these two approaches can provide a more comprehensive understanding of similarity by considering both the semantic meaning of text (captured by embeddings from Sentence Transformers) and the character-level or token-level similarities measured by FuzzyWuzzy.

Providing embeddings generated by Sentence Transformers to FuzzyWuzzy for similarity comparison could potentially reduce the time taken by FuzzyWuzzy to generate similarity scores. This is because the embeddings generated by Sentence Transformers encode the semantic information of the text into fixed-size numerical representations.

When you use embeddings from Sentence Transformers for comparison with FuzzyWuzzy, you bypass the need for FuzzyWuzzy to process and analyze the raw text directly. Instead, FuzzyWuzzy operates on the embeddings, which are already condensed representations capturing the semantic meaning of the text. This can lead to a reduction in the computational time required for FuzzyWuzzy to compute similarity scores since it's comparing numerical representations rather than analyzing the raw text character by character.

When we ran without sentence transformer the time taken to execute and match titles was approximately around 7-10 hours and now this has been reduced to 2.5 hours after implementing Sentence Transformers and Fuzzy Wuzzy together.

Relational Vocabulary:

• A single content detail can be streamed on many OTT platforms. A single OTT platform can have many content details.

• A single content detail can have many genres. A single genre can be associated with many content details.

• A single content detail can have a single category (i.e., either a TV show or a movie). A single category can have many content details.

• A single content detail can have many people. A single person can be involved in many content details.

• A single content detail can be released multiple time, i.e., can have many content release histories. A single content release history is linked to a single content.

• A single person can have many roles. A single role can be fulfilled by many people.

• A single content detail can be released many times. A single release history is associated with only one content detail.

• A single country can have many content release histories. A single release history is linked to a single content detail.

• A single country can have many (fluctuating) populations. A single population (at a given moment) is linked to a single country.

• We have also linked another entity to include the possibility of a single country having many names. A single name is associated with only one country.

import duckdb

class ClassDictCursor():
    def __init__(self, duckdb_con):
        self.con = duckdb_con
        self.column_names = [desc[0] for desc in self.con.description]
        
    def __iter__(self):
        return self
        
    def __next__(self):
        if (next_result := self.con.fetchone()):
            return dict(zip(self.column_names, next_result))
        else:
            raise StopIteration

Functions for Fuzzy Matching Module¶

In this section, we have created a Fuzzy Matching Module to handle similarities in the titles and avoid any repetition.

Algorithm:

  1. Add a column to each CSV file to indicate the OTT platform it was added in.
  2. Compare any 2 datasets.
  3. For Netflix and Amazon, call the function 'find_similar_titles' to create a disctionary of all similar titles having a similarity ratio grater than 80.
  4. Call the function 'combine_and_remove_similar_titles' to create a database of common titles containing information like date it was added to the first platform and second platform and the repeted entries are removed from the database. In simple words we are creating an external data base (stored in the array 'combined_rows') comprimsing of the fuzzy matched titles.
  5. Finally, all other titles that are not similar are added.
  6. Now we compare Netflix with Hulu and Netflix with Disney.
  7. From the next iteration, we compare Amazon with Hulu and Amazon with Disney, and so on.
  8. Finally, we create a new CSV file from this combined database (stored in an erray 'combined_rows').

def add_ott_platform_column_to_csv(file_path,constant_value):   
    # Read the CSV file into a pandas DataFrame
    df = pd.read_csv(file_path)
    df['OTT_platform'] = constant_value
    # Write the updated DataFrame back to a CSV file
    updated_file_path = f'{constant_value}_updated.csv'
    # Replace 'updated_file.csv' with the desired output file path
    df.to_csv(updated_file_path, index=False)

# Function to find similar titles using fuzzy matching
def find_similar_titles(dataset1, dataset2):
    similar_titles = {}
    for title1 in dataset1:
        for title2 in dataset2:
            similarity_ratio = fuzz.ratio(title1, title2)
            if similarity_ratio > 80:  # Adjust the threshold as needed
                similar_titles[title1] = title2
                break
    return similar_titles

# Read local CSV files for Netflix, Hulu, Disney, and Amazon
def read_csv(file_path):
    data = {}
    with open(file_path, newline='', encoding='utf-8') as csvfile:
        reader = csv.DictReader(csvfile)
        for row in reader:
            title = row['title']
            country = row['country']
            date_added = row['date_added']
            director = row['director']
            cast = row['cast']
            release_year = row['release_year']
            rating = row["rating"]
            duration = row["duration"]
            listed_in = row["listed_in"]
            category_type = row["type"]
            
            if title not in data:
                data[title] = {
                    'Country': [], 
                    'Date Added':[],
                    'director':director,
                    'cast':cast,
                    'release_year':release_year,
                    'rating':rating,
                    'duration':duration,
                    'listed_in':listed_in,
                    'type' : category_type
                }
            data[title]['Country'].append(country)
            data[title]['Date Added'].append(date_added)
    return data

def remove_similar_titles(original_dataset, similar_titles):
    for title,matched_title in similar_titles.items():
        if matched_title in original_dataset:
            del original_dataset[matched_title]

def combine_and_remove_similar_titles(data1, data2, similar_titles, combined_rows, combined_titles, platform1, platform2):
    for title, matched_title in similar_titles.items():
        combined_row = {
            'title': title,
            f'country_{platform1}': ','.join(data1[title]['Country']),
            f'date_added_{platform1}': ','.join(data1[title]['Date Added']),
            f'country_{platform2}': ','.join(data2[matched_title]['Country']),
            f'date_added_{platform2}': ','.join(data2[matched_title]['Date Added']),
            'director':data1[title]['director'],
            'cast':data1[title]['cast'],
            'release_year':data1[title]['release_year'],
            'rating':data1[title]['rating'],
            'duration':data1[title]['duration'],
            'listed_in':data1[title]['listed_in'],
            'type': data1[title]['type']
            # Add similar data for other platforms as needed
        }
        combined_rows.append(combined_row)
        combined_titles.add(title)

    remove_similar_titles(data2, similar_titles)

def add_non_similar_titles(combined_rows,combined_titles,data,platform):
    for title, data in data.items():
        if title not in combined_titles:
            combined_row = {
                'title': title,
                f'country_{platform}': ','.join(data['Country']) if 'Country' in data else '',
                f'date_added_{platform}': ','.join(data['Date Added']) if 'Date Added' in data else '',
                'director':data['director'],
                'cast':data['cast'],
                'release_year':data['release_year'],
                'rating':data['rating'],
                'duration':data['duration'],
                'listed_in':data['listed_in'],
                'type': data['type']
                # Add other columns for data
            }
            combined_rows.append(combined_row)
            combined_titles.add(title)

model = SentenceTransformer('sentence-transformers/bert-base-nli-mean-tokens')

# Perform operations based on similar titles found
# For instance, create a combined row for each similar title with data from different platforms
combined_rows = []
combined_titles = set()

# Encode titles using the pre-trained model to get embeddings
netflix_embeddings = {title: model.encode(title) for title in netflix_data}
hulu_embeddings = {title: model.encode(title) for title in hulu_data}
disney_embeddings = {title: model.encode(title) for title in disney_data}
amazon_embeddings = {title: model.encode(title) for title in amazon_data}

# Find similar titles using fuzzy matching on embeddings

netflix_disney_similar_titles = find_similar_titles(netflix_embeddings, disney_embeddings)
netflix_amazon_similar_titles = find_similar_titles(netflix_embeddings, amazon_embeddings)

combine_and_remove_similar_titles(netflix_data,hulu_data,netflix_hulu_similar_titles,combined_rows, combined_titles, "netflix", "hulu")
combine_and_remove_similar_titles(netflix_data,disney_data,netflix_disney_similar_titles,combined_rows, combined_titles, "netflix", "disney")
combine_and_remove_similar_titles(netflix_data,amazon_data,netflix_amazon_similar_titles,combined_rows, combined_titles, "netflix", "amazon")

# non similar rows from netflix
add_non_similar_titles(combined_rows,combined_titles,netflix_data,"netflix")

# re_embedd as similar titles to netflix is removed from these below platforms
hulu_embeddings = {title: model.encode(title) for title in hulu_data}
disney_embeddings = {title: model.encode(title) for title in disney_data}

Functions for the Database Design¶

In the next section, we have created a few commonly used functions to ensure that our code is modular and easy to reproduce. The functions below are for formatting a date, removing special characters from strings, and fuzzy matching (in the case of handling alternative country names).

In [7]:
def formatStringDate(date_string):
    possible_formats = [
        '%d-%b-%y',  # Format: YYYY-MM-DD
        '%B %d, %Y'
        # Add more date formats as needed to cover the possible patterns
    ]
    
    formatted_date = None
    for date_format in possible_formats:
        try:
            parsed_date = datetime.datetime.strptime(date_string, date_format)
            formatted_date = parsed_date.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')  # Convert to desired DB format
            break  # Break the loop if a matching format is found
        except ValueError:
            continue  # Try the next format if this one fails
        
    return formatted_date

def formatStringDateYear(year_string):
    # Convert the year string to an integer
    year = int(year_string)

    # Create a date object with the specified year
    date_object = datetime.date(year, 1, 1)

    # Convert the date object to a string
    date_string = date_object.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')

    return date_string

def remove_special_characters(input_string):
    #replace all characters except a-z and A-Z and 0-9 (alphanumeric values) with ""
    return re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9\s]', '', input_string)

def fuzzy_match_string(string1, string2):
    partial_ratio = fuzz.partial_ratio(string1, string2)
    if partial_ratio > 99.95:
        return True
    else:
        return False

    duration TEXT,

);


DROP TABLE IF EXISTS people;
DROP SEQUENCE IF EXISTS seq_people_id;

    id INT PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT NEXTVAL('seq_people_id'),
    person_name TEXT
);

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS content_details_people;
CREATE TABLE content_details_people (
  content_detail_id INT,
  person_id INT
);

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS roles;
DROP SEQUENCE IF EXISTS seq_roles_id;

    id INT PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT NEXTVAL('seq_roles_id'),
    role_name TEXT
);

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS people_roles;
CREATE TABLE people_roles (
  person_id INT,
  role_id INT
);

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS genres;
DROP SEQUENCE IF EXISTS seq_genres_id;
CREATE SEQUENCE seq_genres_id START 1;

    id INT PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT NEXTVAL('seq_genres_id'),
    genre_name TEXT
);

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS content_details_genres;
CREATE TABLE content_details_genres (
  content_detail_id INT,
  genre_id INT
);



DROP TABLE IF EXISTS content_release_histories;
DROP SEQUENCE IF EXISTS seq_content_release_histories_id;
CREATE SEQUENCE seq_content_release_histories_id START 1;
CREATE TABLE content_release_histories (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT NEXTVAL('seq_content_release_histories_id'),
    date_added date,
    release_year date,
    platform_name TEXT,

Creating countries and young_populations Tables¶

Inserting into conuntries table all the countries available from the combined data. While inserting the countries and its code we fuzzy matched using country_names_codes.csv file for all the country names in combined OTT platform data so that there is no duplicate country names and code. This provides us all the countries needed to be present in countries table and also fuzzy matching with another country names and code dataset enabled us to eliminate having alternate country name as fuzzy matching takes care of closely related countries into one country and also gets the approopriate country code¶

Here we use two csv files and the country_names_codes file scan is resetted to start with 1st row in csv file using csv.seek(0) so that each row in final_combined_data.csv and the content's countries list are fuzzy matched with each of the rows in country_names_codes.csv.¶

In [14]:
with duckdb.connect('duckdb-file.db') as con:
    # code to be uncommented if any error is there in this code cell
    # drop_table = '''
    # DROP TABLE IF EXISTS countries;
    # DROP SEQUENCE IF EXISTS seq_countries_id;
    # CREATE SEQUENCE seq_countries_id START 60;
    # CREATE TABLE countries (
    #     id INT PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT NEXTVAL('seq_countries_id'),
    #     country_name TEXT, 
    #     country_code TEXT
    # );
    # '''
    # con.execute(drop_table);
    sql_placeholder = '''
    INSERT INTO countries(country_name, country_code) VALUES ($country_name, $country_code) RETURNING id;
    '''
    platforms = ['netflix', 'hulu', 'disney', 'amazon']
    with open('final_combined_data.csv') as csvfile1, open('country_names_codes.csv') as csvfile2:
        
        csv_reader_1 = csv.DictReader(csvfile1, delimiter=",", quotechar='"')
        csv_reader_2 = csv.DictReader(csvfile2, delimiter=",", quotechar='"')
        unique_country_name = set()
        countries_codes_visited={};
        for row in csv_reader_1:
            for platform in platforms:
                platform_country = row[f'country_{platform}']
                if platform_country:
                    country_list_per_content = platform_country.split(",")
                    for country in country_list_per_content:
                        country = remove_special_characters(country.strip())
                        csvfile2.seek(0)
                        if country not in countries_codes_visited:
                            for row2 in csv_reader_2:
                                country_code = row2['Alpha-3 code']
                                country_name = row2['Country']

                                if fuzzy_match_string(country, country_name):
                                    param_dict = {'country_name': country, 'country_code': country_code}
                                    if country not in unique_country_name and country:
                                        con.execute(sql_placeholder, param_dict)
                                        unique_country_name.add(country)
                                        countries_codes_visited[country] = country_code

Insert values into content_release_histories table and content_details_content_release_histories table -¶

  1. Here using platformwise date added, release year each of the rows are inserted into content_release_histories as each date_added and in each country should be considered unique value. So we get the country names from the csv file and match it with countries tables and insert those relevant ids for each releases and also we get the content id from content_details_table using content name.
  2. This is where fuzzy matching that was done initially really helps, now we are very sure that csv file title and the database title will have proper match and so to get the content_Detail id is much more easier. If not fuzzy matched and combine the data initially we have the fuzzy match a particular name with all of the rows in the sql and it will take lot of time to execute and also it would be error prone and time taken to test the inserted values to be accurate would be cumbersome.

with duckdb.connect('duckdb-file.db') as con:
    drop_table = '''
        DROP TABLE IF EXISTS content_release_histories;
        DROP SEQUENCE IF EXISTS seq_content_release_histories_id;
        CREATE SEQUENCE seq_content_release_histories_id START 1;
        CREATE TABLE content_release_histories (
            id INT PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT NEXTVAL('seq_content_release_histories_id'),
            date_added date,
            release_year date,
            platform_name TEXT,
            country_id INT
        );
        DROP TABLE IF EXISTS content_details_content_release_histories;
        CREATE TABLE content_details_content_release_histories (
            content_detail_id INT,
            content_release_history_id INT
        );
    '''
    con.execute(drop_table)
    
    sql_placeholder = '''
    INSERT INTO content_release_histories (date_added, release_year, country_id,platform_name) VALUES ($date_added, $release_year, $country_id,$platform_name) RETURNING id;
    '''
    
    sql_content_ids_association_table = '''
    INSERT INTO content_details_content_release_histories (content_detail_id, content_release_history_id) VALUES ($content_details_id,$content_release_histories_id);
    '''
    sql_country_ids_query = '''
    SELECT id FROM countries WHERE country_name = $country_name;
    '''
    
    sql_content_ids_query = '''
    SELECT id FROM content_details WHERE name = $content_name;
    '''
    platforms = ['netflix', 'hulu', 'disney', 'amazon']
    
    with open('final_combined_data.csv') as csvfile:
        csvreader = csv.DictReader(csvfile, delimiter=",", quotechar='"')

        for row in csvreader:
             for platform in platforms:
                platform_country = row[f'country_{platform}'].strip()
                platform_date_added = row[f'date_added_{platform}'].strip()
                # print("platform_date_added:", platform_date_added)
            
                param_dict_content_id = {'content_name': row['title']}
                if not platform_country:
                    # print("inside if loop for null country")
                    continue
                country_list_per_content = platform_country.split(",")
                # print(country_list_per_content)
                for country in country_list_per_content: 
                    # print("inside for loop")
                    country = remove_special_characters(country.strip())
                    # print(":" + country )
                    param_dict_country_id = {'country_name': country}
                    if not (platform_date_added or row['release_year']) or not country:
                        continue

                    country_id_result  = con.execute(sql_country_ids_query, param_dict_country_id).fetchone()
                    content_id_result  = con.execute(sql_content_ids_query, param_dict_content_id).fetchone()

                    if country_id_result is not None and content_id_result is not None:
                        country_id = country_id_result[0]
                        content_id = content_id_result[0]

                    date_added = platform_date_added.strip()
                    stringDate = formatStringDate(date_added) if date_added else None
                    release_year = row['release_year'].strip()
                    stringYear = formatStringDateYear(release_year) if release_year else None
                    # print("date added:", stringDate)
                    param_dict_insert = {
                        'date_added': stringDate,
                        'release_year': stringYear,
                        'country_id': country_id,
                        'platform_name' : platform
                    }
                    
                    con.execute(sql_placeholder, param_dict_insert)
                    content_history_details_id = con.fetchone()[0]
                    
                    param_dict_association_table ={
                        'content_details_id': content_id,
                        'content_release_histories_id': content_history_details_id
                    }
                    
                    con.execute(sql_content_ids_association_table, param_dict_association_table)

Querying¶

Below sample example using sql query to fetch number movies and tv shows that got added in a particular year,particular platform and particular country in comparison with young population percentage. Similar to this we will export the data into csv including all countries, young populations percentage in particular year, and the number of movies and tv shows added in each platform.

In [40]:
%%sql
-- Query for analysis 1 - Through the years, Different countries and its number of tv and movie shows based on each ott platform
SELECT 
    C.id as countryId,
    LOWER(TRIM(C.country_name)) AS country_name,
    EXTRACT(YEAR FROM CRH.date_added) AS release_year,
    LOWER(TRIM(CRH.platform_name)) AS ott_platform_name,
    LOWER(TRIM(CD.category_name)) AS category_name,
    COUNT(*) AS content_count,
    YP.percentage AS young_population_percentage,

FROM 
    content_details CD
JOIN 
    content_details_content_release_histories CDCH ON CD.id = CDCH.content_detail_id
JOIN 
    content_release_histories CRH ON CDCH.content_release_history_id = CRH.id
JOIN 
    countries C ON CRH.country_id = C.id
JOIN 
    young_populations YP ON EXTRACT(YEAR FROM CRH.date_added) = EXTRACT(YEAR FROM YP.year) AND C.id = YP.country_id
GROUP BY 
    LOWER(TRIM(C.country_name)), EXTRACT(YEAR FROM CRH.date_added), LOWER(TRIM(CRH.platform_name)), LOWER(TRIM(CD.category_name)), YP.percentage, countryId
ORDER BY 
    LOWER(TRIM(C.country_name)), release_year, LOWER(TRIM(CD.category_name));

Export file for Analysis - 1¶

Query to understand the relationship between shorter format content ( Movies) and longer format content (TV shows) across OTT platforms and younger population percentage in different countries through the years.¶

In [30]:
# Connect to the DuckDB database
con = duckdb.connect('duckdb-file.db')

# Execute the SQL query
query = """
SELECT 
    C.id as countryId,
    LOWER(TRIM(C.country_name)) AS country_name,
    EXTRACT(YEAR FROM CRH.date_added) AS release_year,
    LOWER(TRIM(CRH.platform_name)) AS ott_platform_name,
    LOWER(TRIM(CD.category_name)) AS category_name,
    COUNT(*) AS content_count,
    YP.percentage AS young_population_percentage,

FROM 
    content_details CD
JOIN 
    content_details_content_release_histories CDCH ON CD.id = CDCH.content_detail_id
JOIN 
    content_release_histories CRH ON CDCH.content_release_history_id = CRH.id
JOIN 
    countries C ON CRH.country_id = C.id
JOIN 
    young_populations YP ON EXTRACT(YEAR FROM CRH.date_added) = EXTRACT(YEAR FROM YP.year) AND C.id = YP.country_id
GROUP BY 
    LOWER(TRIM(C.country_name)), EXTRACT(YEAR FROM CRH.date_added), LOWER(TRIM(CRH.platform_name)), LOWER(TRIM(CD.category_name)), YP.percentage, countryId
ORDER BY 
    LOWER(TRIM(C.country_name)), release_year, LOWER(TRIM(CD.category_name));
"""

# Execute the query and fetch all results
result = con.execute(query).fetchall()

# Write results to a CSV file
with open('Analysis_1.csv', 'w', newline='') as f:
    writer = csv.writer(f)
    # Write header row
    writer.writerow(['Country_id','Country', 'Release_Year', 'OTT_Platform', 'Category', 'Content_Count', 'Young_Population_Percentage'])
    # Write each row of the result to the CSV file
    for row in result:
        writer.writerow(row)

Query to understand the relationship between genres and young population percentage for a country. Does the young population percentage play a role in popularizing certain TV Show/Movie genres?¶

In [32]:
%%sql 
SELECT  c.country_name, 
        EXTRACT(YEAR FROM hist.date_added) AS year, 
        yp.percentage,
        g.genre_name,
        COUNT(*) AS number_of_content_in_genre,
        hist.platform_name
FROM content_details AS cd
JOIN content_details_content_release_histories AS cdcrh ON cd.id = cdcrh.content_detail_id
JOIN content_release_histories AS hist ON cdcrh.content_release_history_id = hist.id
JOIN countries AS c ON hist.country_id = c.id
JOIN young_populations AS yp ON c.id = yp.country_id
JOIN content_details_genres AS cdg ON cd.id = cdg.content_detail_id
JOIN genres AS g ON cdg.genre_id = g.id
GROUP BY    c.country_name, 
            EXTRACT(YEAR FROM hist.date_added), 
            EXTRACT(YEAR FROM yp.year),
            yp.percentage,
            g.genre_name,
            hist.platform_name
HAVING EXTRACT(YEAR FROM hist.date_added) = EXTRACT(YEAR FROM yp.year)
ORDER BY country_name, year

Netflix:

  1. Over the years, after selecting countries of interest, the dashboard below gives us an overview of the young population percentage and the added TV shows and series.
  2. United States and United Kingdom - Even though the young population percentage decreased, the number of movies and TV shows continued to increase, with movies having the upper hand until 2019. From 2020, which we know is the start of the COVID pandemic, the trend tends to fall off, and the overall content added, be it TV shows or movies, has considerably decreased. The same is the case with Canada. Although the attention span of youngsters is reducing year by year and the young population percentage also decreasing through the years - there is no concrete relation between the young population percentage and the number of contents on shorter and longer formats being added. Overall, we can see several movies have the upper hand- there could be a lot of reasons behind it, but the young population percentage appears not to affect the movies and TV shows added to Netflix in these countries.
  3. But if we consider countries like India, where OTT platform content is relatively new, the trend of movies and TV shows added differs significantly. There was a steep downtrend after the year 2020 with movies added.
  4. Japan showed a somewhat different trend, probably because anime content is usually in a longer format, and Japan is known for anime content. We can see the number of TV shows has the upper hand, and the number of movies added is comparatively less. It doesn't have any trend matching the young population percentage in the country.
  5. Overall there is a considerable decrease in number of content added to Netflix post-2020 due to the impact of covid.

Coding through the Challenge¶

The primary challenge and noteworthy aspect of our project revolved around the implementation of the Fuzzy Matching Module. The rationale behind this step was twofold:

  1. Preventing Duplicate Entries: Our goal was to avoid any instances of duplicate entries, such as distinguishing between "The Little Red Riding Hood" and "Little Red Riding Hood." This measure also facilitated the elimination of duplicate entries across various OTT platforms.
  2. Handling Alternate Country Names: We aimed to address the issue of alternate country names, ensuring that distinctions like "The United States of America" and "United States of America" did not result in separate country entries.

To address these challenges, we initially employed the Fuzzy Wuzzy library. However, given the extensive nature of our dataset, with over 8000 rows in each content CSV file, the computation process took more than 7 hours. This prolonged duration was attributed to the algorithm meticulously examining each word of every title, conducting a word-by-word comparison against a pool of over 32000 words.

To enhance computational efficiency, we subsequently leveraged the Sentence Transformers library along with the Fuzzy Wuzzy library. This library operates by embedding strings and comparing their embedded values. Consequently, the computation time was significantly reduced to around 2 hours.

Looking ahead, we envision further improvements by incorporating advanced natural language processing algorithms in our future endeavors.
